window.HOS_KNOWLEDGE = [{"t":"Learn / Red Light Therapy, Explained / What photobiomodulation actually means","x":"Photobiomodulation is the proper name for red light therapy. It means using specific wavelengths of light to help your cells work better. No heat, no UV, no downtime.\n\nThe name matters more than it sounds. Search \"red light therapy\" and you will mostly find people selling devices. Search \"photobiomodulation\" and you will find the research literature, thousands of published studies, and the clinical work behind it. This is a treatment with a genuine scientific field attached, which is not something every wellness trend can claim.\n\nIt was originally called low level laser therapy, until it became clear that LEDs work just as well and lasers were never the point. That shift is what made it practical for treatment rooms like ours.\n\nThe light is non-thermal and non-ionising. In plain terms, nothing is heated, nothing is broken down, and nothing about it resembles a sunbed. Red and near-infrared light is absorbed by structures inside your cells and gently shifts them toward working more efficiently.\n\nThat is the whole idea. Simple, gentle, and quietly well studied."},{"t":"Learn / Red Light Therapy, Explained / How red light feeds your mitochondria","x":"Inside almost every cell are tiny engines that make your energy. Red light helps them run a little better. More energy means your cells can repair, settle down and do their jobs properly. That is the whole idea.\n\nThose tiny engines have a proper name: mitochondria. They sit inside almost every cell, and their job is to turn food and oxygen into energy your body can use. That energy is called ATP, and you can think of it as the fuel that runs every repair and every process a cell carries out.\n\nInside the mitochondria is an enzyme called cytochrome c oxidase, and this is the part that actually absorbs red and near-infrared light. When it does, the leading explanation is that the light displaces nitric oxide, a signaling molecule that can bind to the enzyme during stress and block oxygen from doing its job. Clear the block, and the engine runs more freely. The cell makes more energy, and it makes it more efficiently.\n\nThat light lifts cellular energy is one of the most replicated findings in the field, so we are confident it happens. Exactly how every downstream step works is still being mapped, and honest researchers say so.\n\nWhy this matters to you: a cell with more energy is better at repairing skin, calming inflammation and recovering. You are not being given anything foreign. You are helping your own cells do what they already do, a little better."},{"t":"Learn / Red Light Therapy, Explained / Red vs near-infrared, and why depth matters","x":"Red light works near the surface, on your skin. Near-infrared light is invisible and reaches deeper, into muscle and joints. Different depths, different jobs. A good treatment uses both, which is why one wavelength is only half the story.\n\nLight comes in wavelengths, measured in nanometres, and the number decides how deep the light travels into your body. Red light sits around 630 to 660 nanometres and is absorbed close to the surface, which makes it the wavelength for skin: collagen, tone and the visible signs of aging.\n\nNear-infrared light sits higher, around 810 to 850 nanometres. It is mostly invisible to the human eye, appearing as a faint, dull glow, but it passes through the skin and reaches the tissue underneath, the muscle, joints and deeper structures. This is the band that matters for recovery, stiffness and pain.\n\nNeither one is better than the other. They do different jobs, and the strongest results come from using them together. This is worth knowing before you buy anything, because plenty of cheap devices offer a single wavelength and quietly do half the work.\n\nWhy this matters to you: when you lie in our room, you get both bands at once, surface and depth in the same session. You do not have to pick which problem to treat.\n\nThe science here is settled enough to be practical. Match the wavelength to the target, use both, and you cover far more than one light ever could."},{"t":"Learn / Red Light Therapy, Explained / What the research supports, and what's still emerging","x":"Some uses are well proven: skin, collagen, wound healing, and easing pain and inflammation. Others are promising but still being studied. We would rather point you to the strong evidence than promise you everything.\n\nRed light therapy has an unusually large body of research for a wellness treatment, thousands of studies, but not every study is equal and not every claim is proven. Here is the honest split.\n\nThe strong evidence is for skin, repair and recovery. Improving skin tone and collagen, healing wounds, easing pain and inflammation, and helping muscles recover after exercise are among the most replicated findings in the field. These are the reasons we offer it, and we can stand behind them.\n\nThe emerging evidence is broader: sleep, mood and hair growth, among others. Early results look genuinely interesting, and studies show potential, while more research is still needed before anyone should promise an outcome. We will tell you plainly when something sits in this column.\n\nWhat you will not get from us is the miracle version, the claim that light fixes everything. A treatment with real science attached does not need it.\n\nWhy this matters to you: you can trust the recommendation precisely because we draw this line. When we say something works, we mean the evidence backs it.\n\nThat is the whole picture. Confident where the research is strong, honest where it is still being written."},{"t":"Learn / Red Light Therapy, Explained / What a session feels like and how often to come","x":"You lie down and relax while warm light surrounds you, around ten to twenty minutes. Nothing to endure, nothing to manage. Many people tell us it is the calmest part of their week.\n\nA session is simple. You lie down in our quiet room, the light comes on, and you rest for roughly ten to twenty minutes. There is nothing to endure and nothing to manage. The light is gentle and non-thermal: while high-powered lights emit a mild surface warmth on the skin, it does not heat you from the inside out or make you sweat like a sauna. Most people just close their eyes.\n\nThe part that matters most is not any single session, it is the pattern. Red light therapy is a habit, not a one-off. The cellular changes build with repeated, regular exposure, which is why the research uses courses of sessions rather than single visits.\n\nIn practice, starting around three to five times a week gives your cells steady input while the effects build, and many people settle into a lighter maintenance rhythm once they see results. Think in weeks, not single appointments.\n\nWhy this matters to you: this is exactly why a package makes more sense than paying one session at a time. You are buying a course, because that is how the benefit actually adds up.\n\nPicture six weeks of it: skin that catches the light, easier recovery, a calmer head. That is the real shape of it."},{"t":"Learn / Red Light Therapy, Explained / Safety, contraindications and who should check first","x":"Red light therapy is very safe. No UV, no heat damage, no downtime. A few people should check with a doctor first, including anyone pregnant, taking light-sensitising medication, or with an eye or skin condition in the treatment area.\n\nRed light therapy has a strong safety record. It uses no ultraviolet light, so it does not carry the skin-cancer risk a sunbed does, and it is non-thermal, so it does not burn. For most people the main precaution is simply wearing the eye protection we provide, because the light is bright.\n\nThat said, there are a few situations where we would rather you check with your doctor before booking, and we will say so without being asked.\n\nIf you are pregnant, the evidence is limited, so we take the cautious route. If you take medication or have a condition that makes you sensitive to light, some antibiotics and skin treatments do this, mention it first. If you have a history of skin cancer or an active skin condition in the area being treated, get it cleared. And if you have an eye condition, speak to your specialist.\n\nNone of this is meant to alarm you. Red light is gentle by design, and these are the ordinary, sensible checks any good clinic should raise.\n\nWhy we tell you plainly: we would rather turn a booking away than get this wrong. That is the standard we hold ourselves to."}];
